  "text": "## Dashboard JSON Schema Version Migration Pipeline in Grafana\n\nThe Grafana dashboard migration system implements a comprehensive two-part pipeline with parallel frontend (TypeScript) and backend (Go) migration logic that ensures consistent schema evolution from version 0 to version 42.\n\n### Backend Migration Architecture (Go)\n\n**Migration Runner (apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/migrate.go)**\nThe `Migrate()` function serves as the main entry point. It coordinates a three-stage migration process:\n1. **Initialization**: Calls `Initialize()` which loads the migration function registry via `GetMigrations()` from the schemaversion package\n2. **Preprocessing**: Applies frontend defaults (DashboardModel and PanelModel defaults) before running any schema migrations\n3. **Migration Loop**: Iterates through all necessary schema versions, calling the appropriate migration function from the registry\n4. **Cleanup**: Removes transient properties and normalizes the output to match frontend save model behavior\n\nThe migrator uses a singleton pattern with sync.Once to ensure the migration registry is only initialized once.\n\n**Migration Function Registry (apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/migrations.go)**\nThe `GetMigrations()` function returns a `map[int]SchemaVersionMigrationFunc` containing all 41 version migrations (v2 through v42). The registry maps version numbers to migration functions:\n- Simple versions like V2, V3, V5, V6, V7, V8, etc. are direct function pointers\n- Complex versions like V33 and V36 are factory functions that take a `DataSourceInfoProvider` parameter to dynamically configure datasource migration logic\n\nAll migration functions follow the signature: `func(context.Context, map[string]interface{}) error`\n\n**Individual Schema Migrations (v2.go through v42.go)**\nThe system includes 41 separate migration files implementing incremental schema transformations:\n- **V2** (apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/v2.go): Migrates legacy `services.filter` structure to modern `time` and `templating.list` properties\n- **V16** (apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/v16.go): Major layout migration from row-based system to grid-based layout (24-column grid system). Implements the `upgradeToGridLayout()` logic that matches the frontend's RowArea calculation system\n- **V36** (apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/v36.go): Datasource reference migration, converting datasource names to UID-based references\n- **V38** (apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/v38.go): Table panel cell display mode migration to new cellOptions format\n- **V42** (apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/v42.go): Final schema version for v1 dashboard API (schema v42 is marked as FINAL)\n\nEach migration file is paired with a `v{N}_test.go` test file ensuring correctness.\n\n**Frontend Defaults (apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/frontend_defaults.go)**\nThis critical component replicates frontend defaults before any migrations run:\n- `applyFrontendDefaults()`: Sets DashboardModel constructor defaults (title=\"No Title\", tags=[], timezone=\"\", time.from=\"now-6h\", etc.)\n- `applyPanelDefaults()`: Sets PanelModel constructor defaults for all panels (gridPos, targets with refId:\"A\", fieldConfig structure, etc.)\n- `cleanupDashboardForSave()`: Post-migration cleanup that removes non-persisted properties, null values, and default values to match frontend getSaveModel() behavior\n- Helper functions for panel unique ID assignment, grid position sorting, and null value removal\n\n**Supporting Utilities**\n- `datasource_utils.go`: Helper functions for datasource reference handling\n- `migration_utils.go`: Common utility functions used across migrations\n- `errors.go`: Error handling and migration-specific error types\n\n### Frontend Migration Logic (TypeScript)\n\n**DashboardMigrator Class (public/app/features/dashboard/state/DashboardMigrator.ts)**\nThe TypeScript equivalent implements the same 42-version migration pipeline in the `updateSchema()` method. Key characteristics:\n\n- **DASHBOARD_SCHEMA_VERSION constant**: Set to 42, marked as FINAL - indicates no new schema migrations should be added\n- **updateSchema(old, targetSchemaVersion)**: Main migration method that conditionally applies transformations for each schema version. Early return if `oldVersion === finalTargetVersion`\n\n**Version-Specific Logic in updateSchema()**\n- Versions 2-15: Handle legacy structure transformations (services filter, annotations, timepicker, InfluxDB queries, template variable syntax, etc.)\n- Version 16: Grid layout migration using the RowArea class for panel positioning (width factor = 24/12 = 2)\n- Versions 17-42: Panel-specific upgrades and option migrations (minSpan to maxPerRow, gauge options, table display modes, CloudWatch query migrations, etc.)\n\n**Migration Pattern Matching**\nBoth frontend and backend migrations use conditional checks like `if (oldVersion < N && finalTargetVersion >= N)` to apply transformations only when needed. This allows dashboards at intermediate versions to skip unnecessary migrations.\n\n### Architectural Alignment\n\nThe two implementations mirror each other precisely:\n\n1. **Frontend Path**: JSON dashboard (v39) → DashboardModel → DashboardMigrator.updateSchema() → v42 → getSaveModelClone()\n2. **Backend Path**: JSON dashboard (v39) → migrate.Migrate() → sequence of V{N}() functions → cleanup → v42\n\nKey design principles:\n- **Version-based dispatch**: Both systems use version-to-function mapping for extensibility\n- **Deterministic transformation**: Same input produces identical output regardless of frontend vs. backend execution\n- **Default application**: Frontend defaults must be applied before migrations to match constructor behavior\n- **Schema version 42 as final**: No new schema migrations are accepted; panel-specific migrations should use panel plugin migration handlers instead\n\nThe migration pipeline handles dashboards from schema version 0 (or 1) up to the current version 42, with each intermediate version representing a specific JSON schema evolution that occurred in Grafana's history."
